						               													<description>In &amp;#232;&amp;#144;&amp;#189;&amp;#230;&amp;#155;&amp;#184;&amp;#227;&amp;#129;&amp;#141;&amp;#227;&amp;#131;&amp;#151;&amp;#227;&amp;#131;&amp;#169;&amp;#227;&amp;#131;&amp;#141;&amp;#227;&amp;#131;&amp;#131;&amp;#227;&amp;#131;&amp;#136; (Rakugaki Puranetto), roughly translated as 'Doodle Planet', players create fictional constellations to fit a theme chosen for the round.  A die roll affects how many stars can be drawn. Other players have a chance to guess the correct answer, and if a drawing is not guessed, the drawer connects some of the stars (dots) they have drawn and the other players will have an additional guess.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Points are awarded for guessing correctly and having your drawing guessed correctly.  The points for guessing correctly is always 2, but only the first person to accurately guess is rewarded points; each player may only make a guess on each drawing once.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Points for having your drawing guessed correctly will increase with each incorrect guess made, but if no one gets it, you will lose 1 point.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;The first player to 20 points wins.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;The game comes with a &amp;quot;secret pen&amp;quot; that allows each drawer to write on their drawing what the constellation is in invisible ink that can later be confirmed with a blacklight in the pen's cap.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
